<graph edgedefault="undirected"><node id="&quot;POLLINATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Pollination is the process by which pollen is transferred from the male parts of a flower to the female parts, enabling plant reproduction."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BEES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Bees are a group of insects known for their complex behaviors and reactions to stimuli such as smoke."&lt;SEP&gt;"Bees are insects that contribute significantly to the process of pollination, though they are not formally organized as an entity in the text."&lt;SEP&gt;"Bees are social insects known for their role in pollination and honey production, and their behavior can vary based on interactions with different people."&lt;SEP&gt;"Bees are social insects that live in colonies, capable of learning and performing complex behaviors."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9bc2b94a527d7f2cef89f07403b050b9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3bff3799a6338bd2be390d642031fc2e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1e6e41906583e9d3c61d1d0a4b6f13fe</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 90}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MIDDLE AGES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The Middle Ages is a historical period characterized by the development of protective clothing for beekeepers."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 20}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SECOND ERA&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Second era refers to the period when bees were first brought to North America by the Pilgrims."&lt;SEP&gt;"The Second Era of beekeeping began around 1500 and continued until about 1850, marked by increasing knowledge of bee biology and better beekeeping methods."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 20}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;1500&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"1500 marks the beginning of the Second Era of beekeeping, a period of significant advancements in understanding bee biology and improving beekeeping practices."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 20}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;1850&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"1850 is the year when bees reached the West Coast."&lt;SEP&gt;"1850 marks the end of the Second Era of beekeeping, a period of significant advancements in understanding bee biology and improving beekeeping practices."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 22}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SCIENCE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Science refers to the expanding knowledge in general that contributed to the advancements in beekeeping during the Second Era."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 20}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BEEKEEPERS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Beekeepers are individuals who practice beekeeping and contributed to the advancements in understanding bee biology and improving beekeeping practices."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 20}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;QUEEN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ROLE"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Queen refers to the female bee that lays eggs and is part of the package, essential for the colony's survival."&lt;SEP&gt;"The queen is an egg-laying female in the hive, recognized during the 1500s as a crucial part of bee biology."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1712e3ce0cba3a251f3d6d78a8d75839</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 11}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 65}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DRONES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ROLE"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Drones are male bees, recognized during the 1600s as part of bee biology, though with limited understanding of their role in mating."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 20}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;WORKERS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ROLE"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Workers are female bees, recognized during the 1700s as part of bee biology, and their roles in producing beeswax, pollen collection, and pollination were understood."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 20}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BEESWAX&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Beeswax is produced by worker bees and is used in various hive functions, including the construction of honeycombs."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 20}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;POLLEN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Pollen is collected by worker bees and plays a crucial role in plant reproduction and bee nutrition."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 20}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HONEY BEES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Honey Bees are a specific type of bee known for producing honey and exhibiting certain behaviors in response to environmental stimuli."&lt;SEP&gt;"Honey bees are a species of bee that were introduced to the Western Hemisphere during the Second Era, specifically to North America."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1e6e41906583e9d3c61d1d0a4b6f13fe</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 16}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 83}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NORTH AMERICA&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"North America is a continent where honey bees were introduced during the Second Era."&lt;SEP&gt;"North America is the continent where bees were first brought during the second era of beekeeping history."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 23}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PILGRIMS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Pilgrims refer to the group of people who arrived in North America, bringing bees with them during the second era of beekeeping history."&lt;SEP&gt;"The Pilgrims are a group of people who arrived in North America and are associated with the introduction of honey bees."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 23}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;EAST COAST&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"East Coast is the region where bees first arrived in North America around 1628."&lt;SEP&gt;"The East Coast is the region where honey bees are mentioned to have first arrived in North America, around 1628."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 22}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PROTECTIVE CLOTHING&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Protective clothing refers to the gear designed to protect beekeepers from stings and other hazards during beekeeping activities."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 20}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"LOCATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A hive is the structure where bees live and produce honey, and it is central to beekeeping practices."&lt;SEP&gt;"A hive is the structure where bees live and store honey, and it is crucial for understanding the context of bee space and modern beekeeping practices."&lt;SEP&gt;"Hive is the main location where bees live and perform various activities, including storing pollen and reacting to stimuli."&lt;SEP&gt;"Hive is the structure where bees live and store their honey, serving as their home and workplace."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c2450939cce8947f6b54308a77363272&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3bff3799a6338bd2be390d642031fc2e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-118996eccdc1e632c1523338d0325a42</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 2}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 32}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MATING&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Mating is the process by which bees reproduce, involving the union of a queen and drones."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 20}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HONEY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Honey is a sweet substance produced by bees and is a valuable product of beekeeping."&lt;SEP&gt;"Honey is the product taken from hives, initially obtained by destroying colonies."&lt;SEP&gt;"Honey is used as a home remedy for singers, specifically for soothing the throat."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b1562d6045bde716de4401ba5f862d69&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 21}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;WESTERN HEMISPHERE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The Western Hemisphere is the region where honey bees were introduced during the Second Era, specifically to North America."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 20}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HONEYCOMBS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Honeycombs are structures built by bees using beeswax, used for storing honey and raising brood."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 20}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BROOD&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Brood refers to the developing young bees within the hive, including eggs, larvae, and pupae."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 20}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;POLLINATOR&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ROLE"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Pollinators are organisms that transfer pollen from the male parts of a flower to the female parts, facilitating plant reproduction."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 20}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PLANT REPRODUCTION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Plant reproduction involves the transfer of pollen between flowers, leading to the production of seeds and fruits."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37830172751b4d1f5bd9ccce4fafe89</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 20}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;WEST COAST&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"West Coast is the region where bees reached by 1850, carried there on ships."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 22}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LANGSTROTH HIVE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"TECHNOLOGY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Langstroth hive is a specific type of beehive designed based on the concept of bee space, introduced by Reverend Lorenzo L. Langstroth."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 13}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 71}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BEE SPACE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Bee Space is the natural spacing preferred by honeybees between comb cells, allowing for free movement and use of movable frames within the hive."&lt;SEP&gt;"Bee space is the inviolate space within a hive that bees recognize and leave open, crucial for modern beekeeping."&lt;SEP&gt;"Bee space is the inviolate space within a hive that bees recognize, typically around % inch wide, used for passage and not for building comb or depositing propolis."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-118996eccdc1e632c1523338d0325a42&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6601c8f8aaba892560d94daa97ed47fd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 13}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 71}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;REVEREND LORENZO L. LANGSTROTH&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Reverend Lorenzo L. Langstroth is credited with discovering the concept of bee space, leading to the development of the Langstroth hive."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 13}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 73}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MODERN BEEKEEPING&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Modern beekeeping refers to the practices and techniques developed after the discovery of bee space, particularly the use of movable frames and the Langstroth hive."&lt;SEP&gt;"Modern beekeeping refers to the practices and techniques developed since Langstroth's discovery, including the use of removable frames, beeswax foundation, honey extractors, and queen excluders."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-118996eccdc1e632c1523338d0325a42&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 13}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 72}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;1628&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"DATE"</data>
  <data key="d1">"1628 is the year when bees are believed to have first arrived on the East Coast."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 22}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIVES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"TECHNOLOGY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hives are structures used to house bee colonies, with designs evolving over time."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FRAMES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"TECHNOLOGY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Frames are components inside hives used to support and organize honeycomb structures."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MOVABLE FRAMES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"TECHNOLOGY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Movable frames are a specific type of frame that can be easily removed and repositioned within a hive."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DESTROYING COLONIES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PRACTICE"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Destroying colonies was a method used to obtain honey before the concept of movable frames was developed."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 0}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 21}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CONTROLLING BEES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PRACTICE"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Controlling bees was the constant goal of beekeepers, leading to the development of various hive designs and management techniques."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LANGSTROTH'S DISCOVERY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"DISCOVERY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Langstroth's discovery of bee space in 1850 was a pivotal moment in the history of beekeeping."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 13}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 71}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FATHER OF MODERN BEEKEEPING&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"TITLE"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Reverend Lorenzo L. Langstroth is known as the father of modern beekeeping due to his discovery of bee space."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-032a0987d241a1f1691dfdf14a10e3ea</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 13}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 73}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LANGSTROTH&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Langstroth is known as the father of modern beekeeping due to his discovery of bee space."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-118996eccdc1e632c1523338d0325a42</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 13}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 72}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BEESWAX FOUNDATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"TECHNOLOGY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Beeswax Foundation is a sheet of beeswax impressed with the shape of honeycomb cells, used to guide bees in building combs."&lt;SEP&gt;"Beeswax foundation is a piece of equipment used in modern beekeeping, providing a surface for bees to build comb."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-118996eccdc1e632c1523338d0325a42&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6601c8f8aaba892560d94daa97ed47fd</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 13}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 71}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HONEY EXTRACTOR&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"TECHNOLOGY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Honey Extractor is a machine designed to spin honey from the combs, separating it from the wax."&lt;SEP&gt;"Honey extractor is a piece of equipment used in modern beekeeping to remove honey from comb without damaging the comb."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-118996eccdc1e632c1523338d0325a42&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6601c8f8aaba892560d94daa97ed47fd</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 13}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 71}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;QUEEN EXCLUDER&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"TECHNOLOGY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Queen Excluder is a device placed between brood chambers and honey supers to prevent the queen from laying eggs in the super frames."&lt;SEP&gt;"Queen excluder is a piece of equipment used in modern beekeeping to prevent the queen from entering supers, thus ensuring only worker bees produce honey."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-118996eccdc1e632c1523338d0325a42&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6601c8f8aaba892560d94daa97ed47fd</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 13}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 71}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;COMB&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"TECHNOLOGY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Comb is the structure built by bees using beeswax, used for storing honey and raising brood, and it must fit within the constraints of bee space."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-118996eccdc1e632c1523338d0325a42</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 13}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 72}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PROPOLIS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"MATERIAL"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Propolis is a resinous material collected by bees from tree buds and bark, which they use to seal gaps and protect the hive, and it should not be deposited in bee space."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-118996eccdc1e632c1523338d0325a42</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 13}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 72}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SUPERS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"TECHNOLOGY"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Supers are additional boxes added to a hive to provide more space for honey storage, and they must be placed correctly to respect bee space."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-118996eccdc1e632c1523338d0325a42</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 13}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 72}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ALEX&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Alex is a character who experiences frustration and is observant of the dynamics among other characters."&lt;SEP&gt;"Alex is not explicitly mentioned in the text, but if we assume he is another researcher at the NIH, he would fit this category."&lt;SEP&gt;"Alex is the leader of a team attempting first contact with an unknown intelligence, acknowledging the significance of their task."</data>
