  <data key="d4">5.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Paris Movie Theatre is a location where Jacob and his wife sit during a Sunday afternoon, symbolizing a break from their research."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-0d1852fcdaa63557848de7e718d223a6</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BACTERIA&quot;" target="&quot;VIRUS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">14.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Virus is found within bacteria, with its genes being regulated by external factors like ultraviolet light."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-494c656afa2fa45b32cf5c52326889ec</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BACTERIA&quot;" target="&quot;AMINO ACIDS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">14.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Bacteria can synthesize all twenty kinds of amino acids from a basic medium, highlighting their versatility in amino acid production."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-4eeff2956121f6bd69a6ab83659363d8</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BACTERIA&quot;" target="&quot;GLUCOSE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Bacteria use Glucose as a carbon source in a basic medium to synthesize amino acids."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-4eeff2956121f6bd69a6ab83659363d8</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BACTERIA&quot;" target="&quot;CARBON DIOXIDE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Bacteria use Carbon Dioxide as a carbon source in a basic medium to synthesize amino acids."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-4eeff2956121f6bd69a6ab83659363d8</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VIRUS&quot;" target="&quot;ULTRAVIOLET LIGHT&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Ultraviolet light destroys or removes the repressor, allowing the viral genes to turn on."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-494c656afa2fa45b32cf5c52326889ec</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;ENZYME INDUCTION&quot;" target="&quot;VIRUS ACTIVATION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Enzyme induction is the mechanism Jacob connects to the activation of the virus, involving double-negative logic."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-494c656afa2fa45b32cf5c52326889ec</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;STRUCTURAL PROTEINS&quot;" target="&quot;REGULATORY PROTEINS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">32.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Regulatory proteins control the production of structural proteins, which include enzymes and virus-building parts."&lt;SEP&gt;"Regulatory proteins determine the production of structural proteins based on cellular conditions."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-494c656afa2fa45b32cf5c52326889ec</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;STRUCTURAL PROTEINS&quot;" target="&quot;ACTIVATION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">14.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Activation of viral genes leads to the production of structural proteins."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-494c656afa2fa45b32cf5c52326889ec</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;STRUCTURAL PROTEINS&quot;" target="&quot;CELLULAR REACTIONS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">18.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Structural proteins carry out cellular reactions, which are essential for cell function."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-494c656afa2fa45b32cf5c52326889ec</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;REGULATORY PROTEINS&quot;" target="&quot;CONDITIONS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">18.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Regulatory proteins control the production of structural proteins based on cellular conditions."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-494c656afa2fa45b32cf5c52326889ec</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;REGULATORY PROTEINS&quot;" target="&quot;AMINO ACIDS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">18.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Regulatory Proteins specifically shut off the synthesis of amino acids when they are plentiful, demonstrating a feedback mechanism."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-4eeff2956121f6bd69a6ab83659363d8</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
